			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img src="http://blog.a-pluss.com/wp-content/uploads/a-pluss.com/2012/02/university-essay.jpg" alt="university-essay" title="university-essay" width="200" height="223" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-1937" />If the idea of writing your first essays in university makes your palms sweat and your voice tremble, you are not alone. Indeed, university standards are much higher than those of your high school. However, there is no need to panic. Check this universal recipe to understand what you need to complete high quality <strong>university essays</strong> and receive excellent grades for them.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
<strong>University essay: about this recipe</strong><br />
&nbsp;<br />
This is a classic recipe of a homemade university paper. Certainly, the first thing you should remember about your university projects is that they are all different. You will see that different professors have different requirements depending on their subjects and even personal views. However, most papers deserving good grades share a number of common features which you can find in this recipe.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
<strong>University essay: cooking (writing) time</strong><br />
&nbsp;<br />
Be ready to spend from several hours to several days on writing a good university essay. After completing it, take a break of at least a few hours before coming back and proofreading your paper.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
<strong>University essay: main ingredients</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Understanding of a topic – the deeper the better;</li>
<li>4 cups of investigation: research, reading, synthesis of information and your own consideration;</li>
<li>1 main claim (for a strong thesis statement);</li>
<li>several creative arguments;</li>
<li>logical structure and format;</li>
<li>a handful of amiable tone.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>University essay: directions</strong><br />
<span id="more-1931"></span><br />
<img src="http://blog.a-pluss.com/wp-content/uploads/a-pluss.com/2012/02/essays-in-university.jpg" alt="essays-in-university" title="essays-in-university" width="200" height="142" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-1939" />
<ol>
<li>Understand your topic and bear in mind that most <strong>university essay</strong> questions are debatable. There is not a single right answer and you need to show that you see different sides of the problem. You may use appropriate constructions, such as on the one hand, on the other hand, at the same time, not only…, but also.</li>
<li>Investigate your topic. Find resources related to your topic, read them carefully, analyze and synthesize what you have read and draw your own conclusions. The latter part is especially important. In contrast to high school, summarizing and paraphrasing of what you have read would not impress your tutors. Include your own understanding of the problem.</li>
<li>Make a claim. Express your main conclusion in the form of a thesis statement at the end of the introduction paragraph. When making claims in university essays, try to spark the interest of your readers. The worst possible response to your claim is the reader’s question “So what?” The best response is “I would like to learn more about it”.</li>
<li>Develop creative arguments. When writing essays, university students are expected to predict the counterarguments of potential readers. Imagine your tutors or peers reading your paper and saying “What about…?” Try to answer their questions before they are asked.</li>
<li>Plan your paper. Develop an outline to improve your university essay structure. Decide in what paragraph to include each of your arguments to gain maximum effects. Start writing. Mind university essay word limit.</li>
<li>Add appropriate tone and careful language. Use respectful and amiable tone for your university essays to acknowledge the fact that your position is only one of possible perspectives. Your goal is to show why you think your readers may share your views, instead of persuading the audience that your claims are absolute truths. To achieve this goal, use careful language, such as “these findings suggest that”, “it seems that”.</li>
<li>Add a reference list in proper format. Make a break. Leave your paper for several hours and let it cool down.</li>
<li>Proofread several times before serving. Take care of proper presentation (font, spacing, margins, and citation style).</li>
</ol>
<p>So, this was a classic recipe of an outstanding <strong>university essay</strong>. You may use it to impress your professors during the term or on special occasions, such as exams and applications.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
